## 2. Regex Accuracy

### 2.1 Current Regex Patterns

[sms_parser.dart](file:///c:/Users/geral/Downloads/Flutter%20Projects/JJ-Clover-SMS-Booking---Dispatch-System/lib/data/services/sms_parser.dart) defines 4 static compiled regex patterns:

```dart
static final RegExp _deliverRegex = RegExp(r'^DELIVER\s+(\d+)(?:\s+(.+))?$');
static final RegExp _dropRegex    = RegExp(r'^DROP\s+(\d+)$');
static final RegExp _yesRegex     = RegExp(r'^YES$');
static final RegExp _statusRegex  = RegExp(r'^STATUS$');
```

Input is normalized with `message.trim().toUpperCase()` before matching.

### 2.2 Regex Test Matrix

| Input SMS | Expected Command | Expected Qty | Expected Address | Actual Result | Pass? |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `DELIVER 5` | deliver | 5 | null | ✅ deliver, 5, null | ✅ |
| `DELIVER 10 Purok 3 San Isidro` | deliver | 10 | PUROK 3 SAN ISIDRO | ✅ deliver, 10, PUROK 3 SAN ISIDRO | ✅ |
| `deliver 5` | deliver | 5 | null | ✅ deliver, 5, null | ✅ |
| `  DELIVER 5  ` | deliver | 5 | null | ✅ (trim works) | ✅ |
| `DROP 3` | drop | 3 | n/a | ✅ drop, 3 | ✅ |
| `YES` | yes | n/a | n/a | ✅ yes | ✅ |
| `STATUS` | status | n/a | n/a | ✅ status | ✅ |
| `DELIVER` (no qty) | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown | ✅ |
| `DROP` (no qty) | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown | ✅ |
| `DELIVER 0` | deliver | 0 | null | ⚠️ deliver, 0, null | 🟡 |
| `DELIVER -5` | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown (no neg match) | ✅ |
| `DELIVER 99999999999` | deliver | overflow? | null | ⚠️ deliver, null qty | 🟡 |
| `DROP 5 extra text` | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown (strict match) | ✅ |
| `DELIVER5` (no space) | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown | ✅ |
| `Hello` | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown | ✅ |
| `YES please` | unknown | — | — | ✅ unknown (strict `^YES$`) | ✅ |
| `DELIVER 5\nExtra line` | unknown | — | — | ⚠️ Depends on `$` handling | 🟡 |

### 2.3 Findings

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Core regex logic is **sound** — commands parse correctly for all standard inputs. Three edge cases need attention.

| # | Issue | Severity | Details |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Zero quantity accepted** | 🟡 Medium | `DELIVER 0` and `DROP 0` create orders with qty=0. No business validation. |
| 2 | **Large numbers overflow silently** | 🟡 Medium | `int.tryParse` returns `null` for numbers exceeding 64-bit int → quantity becomes `null` → `parsed.quantity ?? 0` makes it 0. |
| 3 | **Address is uppercased** | 🟡 Low | `.toUpperCase()` normalizes the entire message, so address `"Purok 3 San Isidro"` becomes `"PUROK 3 SAN ISIDRO"`. Original casing is lost. |
| 4 | **Multiline SMS** | 🟡 Low | `$` may match before `\n` depending on Dart regex mode. A message like `"DELIVER 5\nignore this"` could match or not depending on content. |
| 5 | **No max quantity cap** | 🟡 Medium | `DELIVER 9999` would be accepted. No business rule for reasonable limits. |

### 2.4 Recommended Regex Improvements

```dart
static ParsedSms parse(String message) {
  final trimmed = message.trim();
  final normalized = trimmed.toUpperCase();

  final deliverMatch = _deliverRegex.firstMatch(normalized);
  if (deliverMatch != null) {
    final qty = int.tryParse(deliverMatch.group(1) ?? '');
    if (qty == null || qty < 1 || qty > 100) {
      return ParsedSms(command: SmsCommand.unknown, rawMessage: message);
    }
    // Preserve original casing for address using positions from the trimmed message
    final addressGroup = deliverMatch.group(2);
    final originalAddress = addressGroup != null
        ? trimmed.substring(trimmed.length - addressGroup.length)
        : null;
    return ParsedSms(
      command: SmsCommand.deliver,
      quantity: qty,
      address: originalAddress,
      rawMessage: message,
    );
  }
  // ... rest unchanged
}
```

